XI. TO MERCURY

Mercuri, nam te docilis magistro

MERCURY, who taught so well Amphion to move stones with song, —— And thou, O seven-stringod shell, The echoes of whose strains so long

Were mute and joyless‚ but which now

At sanes and rich men’s feasts we hear; — In aptest measures tell me how

To reach obdurate Lyde’s ear.

She, like a filly young and free Frisking and leaping in the fields, Fearing a touch — her liberty N either to spouse nor lover yields. 142
